steps.description:
Be quiet as you can when you move. Don't rub up against the wall, watch where you step, and keep your equipment quiet. As you turn a corner, your body should be planed at an angle so as not to expose any part of your body other than your eye and muzzle, which move as one. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0c/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/0/0c/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/aid427736-v4-728px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The first thing your opponent should see is just a piece of your eye and the muzzle of your weapon (if you are using one) sighted in on them. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/f/ff/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/aid427736-v4-728px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Knowing what to look for is important, if your adversary is concealed. Look for these:
Toe of boots. Fact of life, people don't watch where their feet are. Well, not that often. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/51/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/5/51/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/aid427736-v4-728px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Elbows. Usually, people don't mind their elbow, because it is not a place that commonly comes into contact with surfaces. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8f/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/8/8f/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/aid427736-v4-728px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Equipment such as hats. Chances are, if it's not part of your body you aren't watching what that thing is doing. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8a/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/8/8a/Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet3.jpg/aid427736-v4-728px-Tactically-Move-with-Weapons-Step-8Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
